<Layout title="Obstetric & Maternal Assessment Tools" description="Obstetric and maternal assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Obstetric &amp; Maternal</div>
  <h1>Obstetric &amp; Maternal Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Standardized tools for labor monitoring, fetal assessment, postpartum care, and maternal complications.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bishop Score</strong> — Cervical readiness for labor induction: dilation, effacement, station, consistency, and position. Score ≥8 predicts successful induction; &lt;6 may warrant cervical ripening.</li>
      <li><strong>Leopold Maneuvers</strong> — Four-step systematic abdominal palpation to determine fetal lie, presentation, position, and engagement; performed at each prenatal visit from 28 weeks.</li>
      <li><strong>Non-Stress Test (NST) Interpretation</strong> — Fetal heart rate monitoring for reactivity: reactive (2+ accelerations of ≥15 bpm for ≥15 seconds in 20 minutes) vs. non-reactive; guides further evaluation.</li>
      <li><strong>Biophysical Profile (BPP) Scoring</strong> — Five-component fetal assessment: NST, fetal breathing movements, gross body movements, fetal tone, amniotic fluid volume. Score 8–10 normal; ≤6 may indicate fetal compromise.</li>
      <li><strong>Modified BPP</strong> — Two-component BPP (NST plus amniotic fluid index); used for routine post-dates or high-risk pregnancy surveillance when full BPP not warranted.</li>
      <li><strong>Contraction Stress Test (CST)</strong> — Assesses uteroplacental insufficiency via fetal response to uterine contractions; negative (no late decelerations) is reassuring.</li>
      <li><strong>FIGO Classification of FHR</strong> — International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics intrapartum fetal heart rate classification using baseline, variability, accelerations, and decelerations.</li>
      <li><strong>NICHD FHR Classification</strong> — National Institute of Child Health and Human Development Category I (normal), II (indeterminate), III (abnormal) classification of electronic fetal monitoring patterns.</li>
      <li><strong>Cervical Dilation and Effacement Tracking</strong> — Sequential documentation of cervical dilation (0–10 cm), effacement (0–100%), and fetal station (−5 to +5) using Friedman curve benchmarks.</li>
      <li><strong>Friedman Curve</strong> — Expected labor progress based on time vs. dilation: latent phase (0–6 cm) and active phase (≥6 cm); slower progress guides oxytocin augmentation decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>HELLP Criteria</strong> — Hemolysis, Elevated Liver enzymes, Low Platelets complicating preeclampsia; Class I (platelets &lt;50,000), II (50–100,000), III (100–150,000 with clinical features).</li>
      <li><strong>Postpartum Hemorrhage Risk Assessment</strong> — Antepartum and intrapartum risk factor stratification for PPH (bleeding &gt;500 mL vaginal or &gt;1000 mL cesarean); guides uterotonic prophylaxis and blood product preparation.</li>
      <li><strong>AWHONN PPH Bundle</strong> — Association of Women's Health, Obstetric and Neonatal Nurses standardized hemorrhage prevention, recognition, and response bundle for postpartum hemorrhage.</li>
      <li><strong>REEDA Scale</strong> — Perineal wound healing after episiotomy/laceration: Redness, Edema, Ecchymosis, Discharge, Approximation; scored at postpartum assessments.</li>
      <li><strong>LATCH Score</strong> — Breastfeeding assessment: Latch, Audible swallowing, Type of nipple, Comfort, Hold (positioning). Score 0–10; guides breastfeeding support interventions.</li>
      <li><strong>EPDS (Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale)</strong> — 10-item postpartum depression screen; score ≥13 or any positive response on item 10 (self-harm) warrants immediate clinical evaluation.</li>
      <li><strong>OAA/S Scale (Obstetric Anaesthetists' Association Sedation Scale)</strong> — Observer's Assessment of Alertness/Sedation: responsiveness, speech, expression, and eyes; used for monitoring sedation depth in obstetric patients.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
